=E2=80=8A

UFO Illustration

-----------------------
Artificial Intelligence
-----------------------

Finally, as in our first survey, we asked about A.I. The
first thing I noticed was a sizable drop in the percentage of you saying yo=
u=E2=80=99re not using any A.I. tools, from 35 percent down to 23 percent. =
I wouldn=E2=80=99t assume it=E2=80=99s because you=E2=80=99ve actively chos=
en this path, but rather because nearly every software platform is now shov=
ing A.I. nonconsensually in your face so often you=E2=80=99ve just lost the=
 will to resist. (If you=E2=80=99re reading this report in Gmail, it=E2=80=
=99s probably asking you if you=E2=80=99d prefer an A.I. summary right
now.)

Beyond the aggressive marketing, 62 percent of all Puck respondents said A.=
I. is increasing their business=E2=80=99s productivity=E2=80=94a percentage=
 that surged to 73 percent among survey takers in the media industry. Thank=
fully, so far only 11 percent of respondents reported A.I. having a negativ=
e impact on the size of their workforce or the pace of hiring. And just 5 p=
ercent said A.I. had led to the elimination of jobs at their
place of business.

AI Illustration

Open to A.I.
------------

Is your business using A.I. tools?

Infographic: Are you using A.I. tools?

Productivity boost
------------------

How has A.I. affected your industry?

Infographic:How has A.I. affected your industry?

Of course, the growth trajectory of A.I. ...
--------------------------------------------

will depend on its adoption curve=E2=80=94itself driven by whether
consumers believe it is delivering them real value. And there are early ind=
icators that we may be further along the adoption curve than it appears. Wh=
ile 56 percent of Puck respondents told us they still use Google search =E2=
=80=9Ctoo often to count,=E2=80=9D nearly a third (32 percent) said they us=
e it =E2=80=9Ca lot but not as much as I used to.=E2=80=9D Chatbots aren=E2=
=80=99t yet picking up the slack: Only 3 percent answered that they=E2=80=
=99re using A.I. alternatives all the time. But
increasingly, the line between the two has become blurred: If you ask Googl=
e a question right now, more often than not the top response will be from G=
emini, the company=E2=80=99s large language model.

The other factor in A.I.=E2=80=99s future is how much money is pouring into=
 the sector=E2=80=94and whether the market is overheated. Interestingly, 57=
 percent of respondents in our Finance cohort said they believe the A.I. ma=
rket is a bubble, but that these investments will be justified in the long
run. 37 percent said the market euphoria is outpacing fundamentals. And onl=
y 7 percent said investors were accurately pricing future cash flows right =
now. In other words: Wall Street is largely in agreement that this technolo=
gy will be critically important in the future, but how quickly we get there=
 is up for debate.

Indeed, the speed at which A.I. capabilities grow, and the volume of invest=
ment in the sector, could have major consequences for the U.S.
economy and the Trump administration, which has wrapped its arms firmly aro=
und the billionaires and tech companies placing the biggest bets on A.I., d=
ata centers, and chip manufacturing. We=E2=80=99ll have much more on this t=
opic in the third installment of this survey, launching next quarter. Stay =
tuned.

